# Median imputation
numerical_columns = ['Avg_NumberofSubscription_PerCustomer',
                      'Customer_Avg_NumberofServiceCall_Per_Month',
                      'Customer_Avg_ServiceSuccessRate_PerMonth']

for col in numerical_columns:
    df[col]=df[col].fillna(df[col].median())

from sklearn.preprocessing import OrdinalEncoder

# Ordinal encoding
ordinal_columns = {
    "Service Mix": ["Single Service", "Two Services", "Multi-Service"],
    'Campaign Status':["No Campaign","With Campaign"]
}

encoder = OrdinalEncoder(categories=list(ordinal_columns.values()))
df[list(ordinal_columns.keys())] = encoder.fit_transform(df[list(ordinal_columns.keys())])

Step 4: Global Model Training and Parameter Tuning¶

4.1 Grid Search for Logistic Regression¶

In [22]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Define parameter grid
param_grid = {
    "C": [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10],
    "solver": ["liblinear", "lbfgs"],
    "penalty": ["l2"],
    "class_weight": ["balanced"]
}

# Grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    LogisticRegression(random_state=42), param_grid, cv=5, scoring="roc_auc", n_jobs=-1
)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best global model
global_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
print("Best Parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)

Best Parameters: {'C': 0.01, 'class_weight': 'balanced', 'penalty': 'l2', 'solver': 'lbfgs'}

# Extract feature names (ensure X_train is a DataFrame for feature names)
feature_names = X_train.columns if isinstance(X_train, pd.DataFrame) else [f"Feature {i+1}" for i in range(X_train.shape[1])]

# Extract coefficients from the model
coefficients = global_model.coef_[0]

# Create a DataFrame for feature importance
feature_importance = pd.DataFrame({
    "Feature": feature_names,
    "Importance": coefficients
})

# Calculate absolute values of importance and sort by descending order
feature_importance["Absolute Importance"] = feature_importance["Importance"].abs()
feature_importance = feature_importance.sort_values(by="Absolute Importance", ascending=False)

4.4 Export Result for tableau model¶

  • Identify customers at risk of churn for the next month.
  • Assume that all features remain the same as the most recent month (Month = 6).
  • Update the Month feature to reflect the next month (Month = 7) and use the model to predict outcomes.
In [29]:
# Filter data where month = 6
X_filtered = df[df["Month of Month Sqn"] == 6].copy()

# Change month to 7
X_filtered["Month of Month Sqn"] = 7

# Prepare features (drop target and unnecessary columns)
X_filtered_features = X_filtered.drop(["Max. Churn", "Customer Sqn"], axis=1)

# Transform features
X_filtered_features[numerical_columns] = scaler.transform(X_filtered_features[numerical_columns])

# Perform predictions
y_pred_filtered = global_model.predict(X_filtered_features)  # Predicted outcomes
y_pred_prob_filtered_1 = global_model.predict_proba(X_filtered_features)[:, 1]  # Probability of class 1
y_pred_prob_filtered_0 = global_model.predict_proba(X_filtered_features)[:, 0]  # Probability of class 0

# Create results DataFrame
filtered_results = X_filtered.copy()  # Copy the filtered data
filtered_results['Predicted Outcome'] = y_pred_filtered  # Add predicted outcomes
filtered_results['Predicted Proba of 1'] = y_pred_prob_filtered_1  # Add probability of class 1
filtered_results['Predicted Proba of 0'] = y_pred_prob_filtered_0  # Add probability of class 0

Step 5: Prepare data for tableau what if analysis¶

Tableau’s Aggregation Limitation¶

  • Tableau processes aggregations after calculations and cannot directly pass aggregated fields to TabPy.
  • Only row-level data is sent to TabPy, so aggregated data cannot be processed externally.

Models Require Row-Level Input¶

  • Predictive models need individual rows with all features intact for accurate predictions.
  • Aggregated data lacks granularity, making it unsuitable for row-level predictions.

Preserves Data Granularity¶

  • Flattened data ensures TabPy receives complete row-level information.
  • This enables correct model processing and accurate mapping of predictions back to Tableau.

Resolution : Flatten data:¶

Flattened data overcomes Tableau's inability to send aggregated fields to TabPy, ensuring proper prediction results at the required granularity.
